  "content": "California is taking action to curb locomotive emissions operating within its borders as part of the state's sweeping climate agenda.\r\nOn Thursday, the California Air Resource Board (CARB), a state a\u2026 [+2689 chars]",
  "summary": "California Air Resource Board (CARB) has formulated regulations to reduce emissions from freight trains, making California the first state to do so. Freight trains contribute just 0.5% of overall U.S. greenhouse gas emissions while passenger cars contribute higher. The new regulation, titled 'In-Use Locomotive Regulation,' would disallow the use of any locomotive engines that were constructed over 23 years ago by 2030, require all new locos to be zero-emissions beginning in 2030 and 2035 for freight line haul, and limit the idling time to 30 minutes. According to the CARB, the reduction in emissions will contribute to reducing premature deaths and emergency visits or hospitalizations. ",
