  "title": "Gene-edited cells move science closer to repairing damaged hearts",
  "description": "New research offers a path toward transplants that can fix damage from a heart attack without causing life-threatening arrhythmias.",
  "url": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/science/2023/04/28/heart-attack-stem-cell-treatment/",
  "urlToImage": "https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-apps/imrs.php?src=https://arc-anglerfish-washpost-prod-washpost.s3.amazonaws.com/public/HIAHG2LHTDEY26WUWALM6R7YRQ.jpg&w=1440",
  "publishedAt": "2023-04-28T11:33:14Z",
  "content": "Comment on this story\r\nComment\r\nScientists seeking to combat the nations No. 1 killer have discovered why experiments using cell transplants to repair damage from a heart attack wind up backfiring an\u2026 [+7663 chars]",
  "summary": "Researchers from the University of Washington have made progress\u00a0in finding a solution for treating\u00a0life-threatening heart arrhythmias that can be caused by cell transplants after a heart attack. A study published in the journal Cell Stem Cell details how scientists used gene editing to develop special heart muscle cells that reduced arrhythmia rates by 95%. The new cells are designed to transplant over dead ones, which release a harmful scar tissue. The treatment could pave the way for regenerating the heart and treating cardiac problems ",
